## 4. Layout & Spacing — The Power of Emptiness

### What Qapital does

This is where Qapital truly excels and where Autoceny has the most room to improve:

- **Vertical section padding is enormous.** Each section has roughly 120–160px of padding top and bottom. Some sections have even more. This creates a sense of breathing room that subconsciously communicates luxury and confidence.
- **Content occupies ~60% of the viewport width.** On a 1440px screen, the actual content area is roughly 900–1000px, with everything centered.
- **Every section follows one of two layouts:**
  - **Text left + visual right** (hero, save, invest sections)
  - **Visual left + text right** (budget, dream team sections)
  - These alternate, creating a natural zigzag reading flow.
- **UI mockups are the visual anchors.** Instead of illustrations or stock photos, Qapital shows actual app interfaces — phones, cards, dashboard screens. These serve as both decoration and proof of product quality.
- **Only one CTA per section.** Each section has either a "Learn more" button or nothing. There are no competing links, secondary actions, or distractions.
- **The social proof bar (Editors' choice, 99k+ reviews, $3B saved, $4,900/year) is a single horizontal strip** with generous spacing between each metric. It sits between the hero and the feature sections as a trust accelerator.

### What Autoceny does differently

- The "Jak to działa" (How it works) section is **information-dense**. The dual-column layout showing both the driver and workshop flows is clever, but it creates visual complexity. There are step numbers, sub-headings, UI mockups, side panels, descriptions — all competing for attention simultaneously.
- The vertical rhythm is tighter. Sections feel closer together, which makes the page feel busier even if the actual content volume is similar.
- The hero section tries to do two things at once: explain the concept AND show the interface. Qapital's hero only does one thing — state the value proposition — and lets the phone mockup be purely atmospheric.

### Guidelines for Autoceny

1. **Double your section padding.** Minimum 120px top and bottom for every major section. This single change will have the most dramatic impact on perceived quality.
2. **Constrain content width to 1100–1200px max**, centered on the page.
3. **Adopt the zigzag layout.** Alternate text-left/visual-right and visual-left/text-right for feature sections. Each section should have: one small label (like "Dla Kierowców"), one big headline (5 words max), one short paragraph (2 lines max), and one CTA button.
4. **Break the "How it works" into separate, full-width sections.** Instead of showing all 5 steps at once, give each step (or pair of steps) its own full-bleed section with generous spacing. Consider making the driver flow and workshop flow two separate pages entirely, with the homepage just teasing each.
5. **Use a horizontal social proof bar** between the hero and the first feature section. Include metrics like: number of workshops, number of repair orders completed, average savings, average response time. Style them exactly like Qapital's — icon + big number + small descriptor.
6. **One CTA per section, maximum.** The hero can have two (one for drivers, one for workshops), but every other section should have only one.

